	<h1>Membrane remodeling or fission mediated by dynamin and BAR proteins</h1>
	Dynamin has long been considered as a mechanochemical enzyme essential for endocytosis including neuronal endocytosis. But its mechanism of action remains controversial. The proposed models suggest that dynamin may twist, pinch, and/or stretch the membrane upon GTP hydrolysis in a concerted manner once many dynamin molecules coat on the membrane. We will characterize the underlying mechanosensing and mechanochemical transmission processes that lead to membrane deformation (such as tube formation) and eventually membrane fission.
